eriod, but also to validate domination and inequality, with poets and the educated elite inserted as mediators between the gift of grace and the rest of the people. Offering a literary history of politics in a pre-secular age, Kasa shows that early modern poets mapped salvation onto the most important conflicts of their time in ways missed by literary critics and historians of political thought. Grace, Kasa demonstrates, was an important means of expression and a way to imagine impossible political ideals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aGrace (Theology) in literature. 0aPolitics and literature. 0aProtestant poetry, EnglishyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCowley.  aEarly Modern Literature.  aEducation.  aEpic Poetry.  aHumanism.  aLanyer.  aMilton.  aPolitical Thought.  aPolitics.  aReformation.  aSpenser.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363831040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503638310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503638310/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles